{"id":"2209.01333","submitter":"Zhili Chen Prof.","authors":"Zhili Chen and Jiali Wang","title":"LDP-FPMiner: FP-Tree Based Frequent Itemset Mining with Local\n  Differential Privacy","comments":"12 pages, 8 figures","journal-ref":"Submission to VLDB 2023","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DB cs.CR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Data aggregation in the setting of local differential privacy (LDP)\nguarantees strong privacy by providing plausible deniability of sensitive data.\nExisting works on this issue mostly focused on discovering heavy hitters,\nleaving the task of frequent itemset mining (FIM) as an open problem. To the\nbest of our knowledge, the-state-of-the-art LDP solution to FIM is the SVSM\nprotocol proposed recently. The SVSM protocol is mainly based on the padding\nand sampling based frequency oracle (PSFO) protocol, and regarded an itemset as\nan independent item without considering the frequency consistency among\nitemsets.\n  In this paper, we propose a novel LDP approach to FIM called LDP-FPMiner\nbased on frequent pattern tree (FP-tree). Our proposal exploits frequency\nconsistency among itemsets by constructing and optimizing a noisy FP-tree with\nLDP. Specifically, it works as follows. First, the most frequent items are\nidentified, and the item domain is cut down accordingly. Second, the maximum\nlevel of the FP-tree is estimated. Third, a noisy FP-tree is constructed and\noptimized by using itemset frequency consistency, and then mined to obtain the\nk most frequent itemsets. Experimental results show that the LDP-FPMiner\nsignificantly improves over the state-of-the-art approach, SVSM, especially in\nthe case of a high privacy level.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 3 Sep 2022 05:57:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-07"}
